Chapter 1 — The Concept of Infinity

Before counting, we must understand the unbounded.

· Potential Infinity: A process that never terminates (e.g., counting 1, 2, 3, \dots).
· Actual Infinity: A completed infinite set.
  · Cardinality: The size of a set.
  · Countable Infinity (\aleph_0): The cardinality of \mathbb{N}. A set is countable if it can be put in one‑to‑one correspondence with the natural numbers.
  · Uncountable Infinity (\mathfrak{c}): The cardinality of \mathbb{R}, the continuum.
          Cantor’s Diagonal Argument proves that |\mathbb{R}| > |\mathbb{N}|; there are strictly more real numbers than natural numbers, revealing that infinity comes in different sizes.

The concept of infinity is the first great leap beyond the tangible—it opens the door to limits, continuity, and the infinite processes that define modern mathematics.

Part I — The Language

Before we can describe quantity, structure, or change, we must establish the means of description itself. Part I provides the grammar of mathematics: the formal systems of logic that govern valid reasoning, the language of sets that defines mathematical objects, and the rules of proof that allow us to establish truth. This is the foundation upon which all subsequent mathematical expression is built.

---

Chapter 2 — Foundations: Logic, Sets, and Functions (The Grammar)

Mathematics is expressed in the language of formal logic and set theory. This chapter presents the basic symbols, operations, and structures that constitute that language.

---

2.1 Propositional Logic

Propositional logic deals with statements (propositions) that are either true (T) or false (F) and the logical connectives that combine them.

· Propositions: Declarative sentences that can be assigned a truth value.
· Logical Operators:

Operator Symbol Meaning Example
Negation \neg not \neg P
Conjunction \land and P \land Q
Disjunction \lor or P \lor Q
Implication \implies if...then P \implies Q
Equivalence \iff if and only if P \iff Q

· Truth Tables: Define the meaning of each operator by specifying the truth value of the compound statement for all possible truth values of its components.

---

2.2 Predicate Logic (Quantifiers)

Predicate logic extends propositional logic by introducing variables, predicates (properties or relations), and quantifiers. This allows us to make statements about collections of objects.

· Universal Quantifier:
    \forall x \in A, P(x)
  
    "For all x in A, P(x) is true."
· Existential Quantifier:
    \exists x \in A : P(x)
  
    "There exists an x in A such that P(x) is true."
· Quantifier Negation:
    \neg \forall x P(x) \iff \exists x \neg P(x)
  
    \neg \exists x P(x) \iff \forall x \neg P(x)

---

2.3 Set Theory

A set is a well-defined collection of distinct objects, considered as an object in its own right. Set theory provides the foundational vocabulary for nearly all of mathematics.

· Elementhood:
    x \in A
  
    x is an element of set A.
· Set Definition:
    A = \{x \in U \mid P(x)\}
  
    The set of all x in the universe U such that property P(x) holds.
· Subset:
    B \subseteq A \iff \forall x (x \in B \implies x \in A)
  
    Every element of B is also an element of A.
· Set Equality (Axiom of Extensionality):
    A = B \iff \forall x (x \in A \iff x \in B)
  
    Two sets are equal if and only if they have exactly the same elements.
· Empty Set:
    \emptyset = \{\}
  
    The set containing no elements.
· Basic Operations:

Operation Definition Meaning
Union A \cup B = \{x \mid x \in A \lor x \in B\} All elements in either set
Intersection A \cap B = \{x \mid x \in A \land x \in B\} Elements common to both
Complement A^c = \{x \in U \mid x \notin A\} Everything not in A
Difference A \setminus B = \{x \mid x \in A \land x \notin B\} Elements of A not in B
Cartesian Product A \times B = \{(a,b) \mid a \in A, b \in B\} All ordered pairs

· Power Set:
    \mathcal{P}(A) = \{B \mid B \subseteq A\}
  
    The set of all subsets of A.

---

2.4 Relations

A relation between sets A and B is a subset of their Cartesian product.

· Binary Relation: R \subseteq A \times B. If (a,b) \in R, we often write aRb.
· Properties of Relations (on a single set A):
  · Reflexive: \forall a \in A, aRa
  · Symmetric: \forall a,b \in A, aRb \implies bRa
  · Transitive: \forall a,b,c \in A, (aRb \land bRc) \implies aRc
  · Equivalence Relation: A relation that is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive. Equivalence relations partition a set into disjoint equivalence classes.
· Order Relations:
  · Partial Order: Reflexive, antisymmetric (aRb \land bRa \implies a = b), and transitive.
  · Total Order: A partial order where every pair of elements is comparable (\forall a,b, aRb \lor bRa).

---

2.5 Functions

A function is a special type of relation that assigns to each element of the domain exactly one element of the codomain.

· Definition: A function f: A \to B is a relation f \subseteq A \times B such that:
  · \forall a \in A, \exists b \in B : (a,b) \in f (every element of the domain is assigned a value)
  · If (a, b_1) \in f and (a, b_2) \in f, then b_1 = b_2 (the assignment is unique)
· Notation: For (a,b) \in f, we write f(a) = b.
· Domain and Codomain: A is the domain, B is the codomain. The range (or image) is \{f(a) \mid a \in A\} \subseteq B.
· Types of Functions:
  · Injective (One-to-one): f(a_1) = f(a_2) \implies a_1 = a_2. Distinct inputs map to distinct outputs.
  · Surjective (Onto): \forall b \in B, \exists a \in A : f(a) = b. Every element of the codomain is hit.
  · Bijective: Both injective and surjective. A bijection establishes a perfect pairing between A and B.
· Composition: For f: A \to B and g: B \to C, the composition g \circ f: A \to C is defined by (g \circ f)(a) = g(f(a)).
· Inverse Function: If f: A \to B is bijective, there exists a unique function f^{-1}: B \to A such that f^{-1}(f(a)) = a and f(f^{-1}(b)) = b.

