Chapter 15 — Discrete Mathematics and Information Theory (The Logic of Machines)

Discrete mathematics studies countable, distinct structures—the mathematics of the digital world. Information theory, born from the need to quantify communication, provides the fundamental limits of data compression and transmission. Together, they form the theoretical foundation of computer science and the digital age.

---

15.1 Combinatorics: The Art of Counting

Combinatorics deals with counting, arrangement, and combination of objects.

· Fundamental Counting Principle: If one event can occur in m ways and another in n ways, the two events can occur in m \times n ways.
· Permutations: Ordered arrangements.
  · Permutations of n distinct objects: n!
  · Permutations of k objects chosen from n: P(n, k) = \frac{n!}{(n-k)!}
· Combinations: Unordered selections.
  · Number of ways to choose k objects from n:
    \binom{n}{k} = \frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}
  · Properties:
    · \binom{n}{k} = \binom{n}{n-k}
    · \binom{n}{0} = \binom{n}{n} = 1
    · Pascal's Identity: \binom{n}{k} = \binom{n-1}{k-1} + \binom{n-1}{k}
· Binomial Theorem:
  (x + y)^n = \sum_{k=0}^n \binom{n}{k} x^{n-k} y^k
· Inclusion-Exclusion Principle: For finite sets A_1, \dots, A_n:
  \left| \bigcup_{i=1}^n A_i \right| = \sum_i |A_i| - \sum_{i<j} |A_i \cap A_j| + \sum_{i<j<k} |A_i \cap A_j \cap A_k| - \cdots
· Pigeonhole Principle: If n items are placed into m containers and n > m, then at least one container contains more than one item.

---

15.2 Graph Theory

A graph is a mathematical structure modeling pairwise relationships between objects.

· Definition: A graph G = (V, E) consists of:
  · V: a set of vertices (nodes)
  · E: a set of edges (pairs of vertices)
· Types of Graphs:
  · Undirected: Edges are unordered pairs \{u, v\}
  · Directed (Digraph): Edges are ordered pairs (u, v)
  · Simple: No loops (edges from a vertex to itself) and no multiple edges
  · Weighted: Edges have associated numbers (weights)
· Basic Terminology:
  · Degree of a vertex: number of edges incident to it (undirected)
  · In-degree/Out-degree: For directed graphs
  · Path: Sequence of vertices where consecutive vertices are adjacent
  · Cycle: A path that starts and ends at the same vertex
  · Connected: There is a path between any two vertices
  · Tree: A connected graph with no cycles
  · Complete Graph K_n: Every pair of vertices is connected by an edge
· Handshaking Lemma: In any undirected graph:
  \sum_{v \in V} \deg(v) = 2|E|
· Graph Representations:
  · Adjacency Matrix: A_{ij} = 1 if vertices i and j are adjacent
  · Adjacency List: List of neighbors for each vertex
· Important Graph Families:
  · Trees: Connected, acyclic graphs. A tree with n vertices has exactly n-1 edges.
  · Bipartite Graphs: Vertices can be partitioned into two sets such that all edges go between sets.
  · Planar Graphs: Can be drawn in the plane without edges crossing.
· Eulerian and Hamiltonian Paths:
  · Eulerian Path: Visits every edge exactly once. Exists iff at most two vertices have odd degree.
  · Hamiltonian Path: Visits every vertex exactly once. No simple characterization exists.

---

15.3 Boolean Algebra and Logic Gates

Boolean algebra is the algebra of binary values (0 and 1, or false and true). It is the mathematical foundation of digital circuit design.

· Basic Operations:
  · AND (\land): x \land y = 1 iff x = 1 and y = 1
  · OR (\lor): x \lor y = 1 iff x = 1 or y = 1
  · NOT (\neg): \neg x = 1 iff x = 0
· Truth Tables:

x y x \land y x \lor y \neg x
0 0 0 0 1
0 1 0 1 1
1 0 0 1 0
1 1 1 1 0

· Boolean Identities:
  · Commutativity: x \land y = y \land x, x \lor y = y \lor x
  · Associativity: (x \land y) \land z = x \land (y \land z), similarly for OR
  · Distributivity: x \land (y \lor z) = (x \land y) \lor (x \land z)
  · De Morgan's Laws:
    · \neg (x \land y) = (\neg x) \lor (\neg y)
    · \neg (x \lor y) = (\neg x) \land (\neg y)
  · Absorption: x \land (x \lor y) = x, x \lor (x \land y) = x
· Logic Gates: Physical implementations of Boolean operations—the building blocks of digital circuits.

---

15.4 Binary Representation

Binary is the base-2 number system, using only digits 0 and 1. It is the native language of computers.

· Binary Digits (Bits): The fundamental units of digital information.
· Conversion:
  · Binary to decimal: 1011_2 = 1\cdot 2^3 + 0\cdot 2^2 + 1\cdot 2^1 + 1\cdot 2^0 = 8 + 0 + 2 + 1 = 11_{10}
  · Decimal to binary: Repeated division by 2, reading remainders backward.
· Binary Arithmetic: Follows same rules as decimal, but simpler:
  · 0 + 0 = 0, 0 + 1 = 1, 1 + 1 = 10 (carry 1)
  · 0 \times 0 = 0, 0 \times 1 = 0, 1 \times 1 = 1
· Other Bases: Hexadecimal (base 16) and octal (base 8) are commonly used as shorthand for binary.
· Two's Complement: Representation for signed integers in computers.

---

15.5 Algorithm Analysis and Complexity

An algorithm is a finite sequence of well-defined instructions for solving a problem. Complexity theory studies the resources (time, memory) required by algorithms.

· Time Complexity: The number of basic operations as a function of input size n.
· Big-O Notation: Describes the asymptotic upper bound of a function.
  f(n) = O(g(n)) \iff \exists C, n_0 > 0 : |f(n)| \leq C|g(n)| \ \forall n \geq n_0
· Common Complexity Classes:

Class Name Example
O(1) Constant Array access
O(\log n) Logarithmic Binary search
O(n) Linear Linear search
O(n \log n) Linearithmic Merge sort, quicksort (average)
O(n^2) Quadratic Bubble sort, nested loops
O(2^n) Exponential Subset generation
O(n!) Factorial Permutation generation

· Space Complexity: The amount of memory required.

---

15.6 P vs NP

One of the most important open problems in computer science and mathematics.

· P (Polynomial Time): Problems that can be solved in polynomial time by a deterministic Turing machine (efficiently solvable).
· NP (Nondeterministic Polynomial Time): Problems whose solutions can be verified in polynomial time.
· NP-Complete: The hardest problems in NP. If any NP-complete problem can be solved in polynomial time, then all NP problems can be solved in polynomial time (P = NP).
· Examples of NP-Complete Problems:
  · Boolean satisfiability (SAT)
  · Traveling salesman problem (decision version)
  · Graph coloring
  · Knapsack problem
· Significance: The question P \stackrel{?}{=} NP asks whether problems that are easy to check are also easy to solve. Most researchers believe P \neq NP, but a proof remains elusive. The answer has profound implications for cryptography, optimization, and our understanding of computation.

---

15.7 Information Theory

Information theory, founded by Claude Shannon in 1948, quantifies information and establishes fundamental limits on data compression and communication.

· Self-Information: The information content of an event x with probability p(x):
  I(x) = -\log_2 p(x) \quad \text{(bits)}
  
  Rare events carry more information than common events.
· Entropy (H): The average information content of a random variable.
  H(X) = -\sum_{i} p(x_i) \log_2 p(x_i) \quad \text{(bits)}
  · Interpretation: Entropy measures uncertainty or the minimum number of bits needed on average to encode outcomes of X.
  · Maximum: Achieved by uniform distribution (maximum uncertainty).
  · Minimum: 0 for deterministic variables (no uncertainty).
· Joint Entropy: H(X, Y) = -\sum_x \sum_y p(x, y) \log_2 p(x, y)
· Conditional Entropy: H(Y \mid X) = \sum_x p(x) H(Y \mid X = x)
· Mutual Information: The amount of information one random variable contains about another.
  I(X; Y) = H(X) - H(X \mid Y) = H(Y) - H(Y \mid X)
· Properties:
  · I(X; Y) \geq 0, with equality iff X and Y are independent.
  · I(X; Y) = H(X) + H(Y) - H(X, Y)

---

15.8 Coding Theory

· Source Coding Theorem (Shannon's First Theorem): For a source with entropy H, it is possible to compress data to an average of H bits per symbol, but not less.
· Huffman Coding: An optimal prefix-free coding algorithm that achieves compression arbitrarily close to the entropy limit.
· Channel Capacity: The maximum rate at which information can be reliably transmitted over a communication channel.
· Noisy Channel Coding Theorem (Shannon's Second Theorem): For a channel with capacity C, it is possible to transmit information at any rate R < C with arbitrarily low error probability, using appropriate coding.
· Error-Correcting Codes: Add redundancy to detect and correct errors introduced during transmission.
  · Hamming Codes: Simple single-error-correcting codes.
  · Reed–Solomon Codes: Used in CDs, QR codes, and space communication.
  · LDPC Codes: Modern codes approaching the Shannon limit.

---

15.9 The Fourier Transform

The Fourier transform decomposes a function into its constituent frequencies. It is fundamental to signal processing, image compression, and countless engineering applications.

· Continuous Fourier Transform:
  \hat{f}(\xi) = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} f(x) e^{-2\pi i x \xi} \, dx
  
  f(x) = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \hat{f}(\xi) e^{2\pi i x \xi} \, d\xi
· Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT): For a sequence x_0, x_1, \dots, x_{N-1}:
  X_k = \sum_{n=0}^{N-1} x_n e^{-2\pi i k n / N}
· Fast Fourier Transform (FFT): An efficient algorithm for computing the DFT in O(N \log N) time, revolutionizing digital signal processing.
· Applications:
  · JPEG image compression
  · MP3 audio compression
  · Solving partial differential equations
  · Spectral analysis
  · Convolution and filtering

